 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCold has long been a fixture of Russian identity both within and beyond the borders of Russia and the Soviet Union, even as the ongoing effects of climate change complicate its meaning and cultural salience. The Russian Cold assembles fascinating new contributions from a variety of scholarly traditions, offering new perspectives on how to understand this mainstay of Russian culture and history. In chapters encompassing such diverse topics as polar exploration, the Eastern Front in World War II, and the iconography of hockey, it explores the multiplicity and ambiguity of “cold” in the Russian context and demonstrates the value of environmental-historical research for enriching national and imperial histories.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCold. 0aHuman beingsxEffect of environment onzRussia (Federation) 0aHuman beingsxEffect of environment onzRussia (Federation). 0aNational characteristics, Russian. 0aRussians. 0aWinterxSocial aspectszRussia (Federation) 0aWinterxSocial aspectszRussia (Federation). 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aHistory: 18th/19th Century, History: 20th Century to Present, Environmental Studies (General).1 aAnanyev, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBulgakowa, Oksana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerzberg, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerzberg, Julia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKuzminykh, Aleksandr, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMauer, Roman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPopov, Aleksei, econtributor.4ctb4h